<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; organization (with particular safeguards in place) to have scripts</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; run</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; unattended that operate on behalf of that person or organization.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; Ok, given you&#39;re going to phrase it that way - why/how is what you</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; propose different from the way Grid jobs work now; proxy certificates</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; were invented to provide the kind of delegation you seem to</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; describe here,</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; with some trade off of security and convenience.   (It sounds to me</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; like you&#39;re running (sort of) reduced or test Grid jobs and  also</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; maybe reading stats or logs from production services.)</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; (When I talk about proxies, I am only talking about proxy</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; certificates viz</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; <a href='http&#58;//www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc3820.txt' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc3820.txt</a></font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; There are no shades of meaning in play.)</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; more onerous) methods later. While I personally don&#39;t mind</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; renewing some</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; credential manually once per week, one has to allow some mechanism fo</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; delegation to another person otherwise one family emergency could</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; mean</font>
<div id='show_1685220613' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_1685220613'><font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; Cynically, I would argue that that is in fact how most things seem</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; to work anyway. (How isn&#39;t that true now?  Aren&#39;t Kerberos principals</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; restricted to an individual? Or better how do you deal with this</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; problem</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; now?)</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The use of VOMS proxy certs could provide the flexibilty you&#39;re</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; looking</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; for in this case, because a role could be created that various people</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; can get.  The voms proxy certs would then present that role assertion</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; when setting up and running jobs.  Your applications, tho, will</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; have to</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; know what this role means.  (Unfortunately, I have learned recently</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; that</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; OSG is going in a different direction and is not really using VOMS</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; proxies as bearer credentials so the authorization problem is more</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; complicated</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; than that.)  You do become dependent on the VOMS management, one</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; way or the</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; other, to administer and manage the roles.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; You seemed to express some dissatisfaction with the time to live of</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; proxy</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; certs.  What is the rite TTL for this kind of work?</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; Thanks, ==mwh</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
