<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62; Let&#39;s see if I understand correctly what you are specifying.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62; You want to be issued user (personal) certificates and not have a</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62; requirement to maintain a passphrase on the associated private</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62; key.    This key pair will be used to authenticate to VOMS and</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62;&#62; create proxy certs useful for some role (never mind what).</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; Not quite. I want to be able to authorize an automated process to</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; obtain VO credentials without having to be there at the time. I</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; don&#39;t care whether that happens as you say or via some other pre-</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; authorization mechanism. To phrase this differently&#58;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; I need to have something that is logically more-or-less a host</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; cert obtain a voms proxy.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The interoperability requirements that govern the DOEGrids CA</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; policy require that the private key of human end entity</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; certs be protected by some kind of passphrase (&c).</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; (See <a href='http&#58;//www.eugridpma.org/guidelines/IGTF-AP-' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//www.eugridpma.org/guidelines/IGTF-AP-</a></font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; classic-20050930-4-0.html#_Toc116323585</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; )</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; DOEGrids CA doesn&#39;t manage private keys of end entities.</font>
<div id='show_2077869281' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_2077869281'><font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; Grids only support software based crypto stores (tokens)</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; (that is, files).</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; Even if Grids supported hardware tokens, they too have to be</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; protected with PINs or passphrases or they are operationally the</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; same as software based crypto.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The bottom line on this would be that your specification seems to</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; reduce to what I wrote above in this case, that you need passwordless</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; private keys.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; As you say above, this seems like something that should be done</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; by a proxy certificate, whether human or host - based.  Since you</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; are currently using a Kerberos-based service as the basis of</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; identification, could your proposed operation use a proxy cert</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; as the basis for these services?</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; I cannot be required to do anything interactive at the time; nor</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; do I wish to have to type in a passphrase at too short an interval</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; -- this will be an automatic process running (say) one to four</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; times per day.</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; I understand from talking to a colleague here that there was a GGF</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; proposal for exactly this, and it was referred to as,</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; &#34;certificates for automated clients.&#34; I believe the  suggestion</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; was to have OU=robots. The document reference was, &#34;draft-ggf-</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;&#62; caops-auto-client-certs.&#34;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; That document did not proceed in GGF.  The word &#34;robot&#34; has</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; a wide variety of probably conflicting meanings (eg there is</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; currently at least one other &#34;robot&#34; cert proposal floating</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; around but it is focused on services).</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62;</font>
