<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; ESnet/LBNL</font></pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='3592#1181257193'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2007-06-07T22:59:53+00:00">Jun 7, 2007 10:59 PM UTC</time> by <b>Joel Worden</b><a class="anchor" name="1181257193">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>From&#58; Chris Green &#60;greenc@....&#62;
To&#58; helm@....
cc&#58; helm@...., Grid Operations Center &#60;goc@....&#62;,
Don Petravick &#60;petravick@....&#62;, Ruth Pordes &#60;ruth@....&#62;, Keith Chadwick
&#60;chadwick@....&#62;,
Doug Olson &#60;dlolson@....&#62;
Subject&#58; Re&#58; [info-doegrids] Need personal robot certs
Date-Sent&#58; Thursday, June 07, 2007 5&#58;44 PM -0500

Hi,

Thanks for all your input on this. For me personally, the workaround is to use the
kerberos facility; however many of the people at whom my test script is named will
only have access to the DOEGrids CA. I believe this is definitely an idea whose time
has come&#58; the use cases are there, the desire for a secure solution is there; and one
needs to fill the vacuum before less savory workarounds are found by individuals and
the enforcement arm has to kick into gear.

I don&#39;t know quite what is meant by &#34;proxy&#34; here. That word is overloaded and has
many shades of meaning. I need some safe, secure and acceptable method of having&#58;

voms-proxy-init &#60;blah&#62;

in a script without having to be physically there at execution time to type a
password, punch in a number or prick my finger. I understand that myproxy, unless
also running with kerberos, allows a simple password; while this solution is
available now, I don&#39;t really want to be encouraging people to use it to then have to
swap to safer (but possibly more onerous) methods later. While I personally don&#39;t
mind renewing some credential manually once per week, one has to allow some mechanism
for delegation to another person otherwise one family emergency could mean essential
things don&#39;t get done.

As I think either Mike or Doug said&#58; my use case here isn&#39;t exactly a &#34;service,&#34; like
backup to a grid-based storage resource; a VO manager or other responsible would be
gathering information about multiple sites that nominally support that VO and
<div id='show_2119711770' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_2119711770'>compiling that information from VORS, ReSS/BDII, fork jobs and batch jobs to those
sites. This is really an automated user/client operation, not a service. In these
days of increased automation across the board, I think it is reasonable to expect and
allow a person or organization (with particular safeguards in place) to have scripts
run unattended that operate on behalf of that person or organization.

I&#39;m hoping to get this discussed in other fora too, with the aim of getting momentum
up towards a solution sooner rather than later.

Thanks again for your help and time,
Chris.

--
Chris Green &#60;greenc@....&#62;, FNAL CD/SCF/GRID.
&#39;Phone (630) 840-2167.
IRC&#58; greenc (jabber.fnal.gov); chissgreen (AIM, Yahoo);
chissg@.... (MSNM); chris.h.green (Google Talk).
